Reports usages of backward GOTO statements and GOTO statements used to exit a loop.
<p>The extensive use of GOTO statements is generally
  not recommended. For details, see <a href="https://www.ibm.com/docs/no/db2/11.5?topic=procedures-goto-statement-in-sql">GOTO statement in
    SQL
    procedures at ibm.com</a>.</p>

<p>Instead of jumping back to a previous statement using GOTO, consider using a loop.</p>
<p>Instead of exiting the WHILE loop with GOTO, consider using other control-of-flow statements (for example, RETURN or BREAK).</p>
<p>Example (Oracle):</p>
<pre><code>CREATE PROCEDURE test(n INT) AS
DECLARE
    x INT;
BEGIN
    x := 0;
    GOTO a;
    &lt;&lt;a&gt;&gt; x := 1;
    IF (n = 0) THEN
        GOTO a;
    END IF;
    WHILE TRUE
        LOOP
            GOTO b;
        END LOOP;
    &lt;&lt;b&gt;&gt; x := 3;
END;</code></pre>
